Classification: Classification is a supervised learning technique used to predict categorical outputs. The model learns from labeled data and assigns new data to one of the predefined classes. It is commonly used in applications such as spam detection, fraud detection, and disease prediction.

How Classification Works

             Training Data
(Input Features + Class Labels)
               │
               ▼
         Train the Model
               │
               ▼
      Learn Classification Rules
               │
               ▼
       Predict New Class Label

Real-Life Example
Email Spam Detection
Email Text	Output
Win ₹10 lakh now!	Spam
Meeting at 3 PM	Not Spam
Claim your prize	Spam

Types of Classification
There are four main types of classification.

Classification
 │
├── 1. Binary Classification
├── 2. Multi-Class Classification
├── 3. Multi-Label Classification
 └── 4. Imbalanced Classification

1. Binary Classification
Definition
Binary Classification predicts one of two possible classes. Each input belongs to only one of the two categories.
Example
Email Spam Detection
Email	Output
Win Money	Spam
Office Meeting	Not Spam
Possible Outputs:
	• Yes / No 
	• Pass / Fail 
	• True / False 
	• Fraud / Not Fraud 
Applications
	• Spam Detection 
	• Disease Detection 
	• Loan Approval 
	• Fraud Detection 

2. Multi-Class Classification
Definition
Multi-Class Classification predicts one class from three or more possible categories. Each input belongs to only one class.
Example
Animal Classification
Image	Output
🐶	Dog
🐱	Cat
🐦	Bird
Possible Classes:
	• Dog 
	• Cat 
	• Bird 
	• Horse 
The model predicts only one class.
Applications
	• Handwritten Digit Recognition (0–9) 
	• Animal Classification 
	• Fruit Classification 
	• Language Identification 

3. Multi-Label Classification
Definition
Multi-Label Classification allows a single input to belong to multiple classes at the same time.
Example
Movie Genres
Movie	Output
Avengers	Action, Adventure, Sci-Fi
A movie can belong to several genres simultaneously.
Applications
	• Image Tagging 
	• News Categorization 
	• Music Genre Classification 
	• Document Tagging 

4. Imbalanced Classification
Definition
Imbalanced Classification occurs when one class has many more examples than the other class. The model needs special techniques to learn both classes effectively.
Example
Credit Card Fraud Detection
Transactions	Count
Normal	99,000
Fraud	1,000
The model must learn to detect the rare fraud cases.
Applications
	• Fraud Detection 
	• Disease Diagnosis 
	• Cybersecurity 
	• Insurance Claim Detection 

Common Classification Algorithms
Algorithm	Used For
Logistic Regression	Binary Classification
Decision Tree	Binary & Multi-Class
Random Forest	Binary & Multi-Class
K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)	Classification
Support Vector Machine (SVM)	Binary & Multi-Class
Naive Bayes	Text Classification & Spam Detection

